37:53.238 --> 37:56.341 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
site.

37:56.374 --> 38:10.788 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now: how NASA is
trying to
fight fire with fire in space.

38:10.822 --> 38:14.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Researchers are conducting new
experiments
that would limit that particular
danger for

38:14.993 --> 38:16.928 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
future space travel.

38:16.961 --> 38:21.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Science correspondent Miles
O'Brien has the
story. It's part of our weekly
series on the

38:21.432 --> 38:23.768 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Leading Edge of science and
technology.

38:23.801 --> 38:30.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN GRUNSFELD, NASA: We are
crossing an international
boundary. We are on the U.S.
side now, and

38:31.009 --> 38:34.345 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
now we are on the Russian Mir
space station.

38:34.379 --> 38:40.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: By 1997, the
Russian space
station Mir was 11 years old and
showing its

38:40.185 --> 38:45.790 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
age. During the fifth shuttle
mission to the
station, astronaut John
Grunsfeld documented

38:45.823 --> 38:51.930 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the warren of modules brimming
with a disorienting
maze of cables, hoses and trash.

38:51.963 --> 38:54.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN GRUNSFELD: I feel like I am
exploring
a cave.

38:54.799 --> 38:58.169 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Can you imagine
being in a
fire here?

38:58.203 --> 39:03.074 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
U.S. astronaut Jerry Linenger
lived that nightmare
on February 23, 1997.

39:03.107 --> 39:10.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JERRY LINENGER, NASA: The fire
was basically
in this region here with the
flames shooting

39:10.281 --> 39:12.050 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
across this way.

39:12.083 --> 39:15.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The source was a
canister filled
with chemicals designed to
generate oxygen.

39:15.420 --> 39:20.992 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JERRY LINENGER: You have got a
two- or three-foot
flame, blowtorch-like in
intensity, sparks

39:21.025 --> 39:23.895 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
flying off the end of it. It
looks like a
hundred sparklers all at once.

39:23.928 --> 39:28.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Linenger and his
Russian crewmates
donned masks and frantically
fought the fire.

39:29.000 --> 39:34.639 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JERRY LINENGER: The fire took
about 14 minutes
total, and 14 minutes is a long
time with

39:34.672 --> 39:40.478 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a roaring fire and a blackout
from the smoke,
and no place to go. And if it
were any bigger,

39:40.511 --> 39:42.947 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm pretty darn sure we would
have lost that
spacecraft.

39:42.981 --> 39:46.584 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: For NASA
scientists and engineers,
it was a big wakeup call.

39:46.618 --> 39:49.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GARY RUFF, NASA Glenn Research
Center: One
of the things that you learn is,
we really

39:49.654 --> 39:51.856 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
didn't have a way to put that
fire out.

39:51.890 --> 39:57.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Gary Ruff is a
scientist at
NASA's Glenn Research Center in
Cleveland,

39:57.929 --> 40:03.201 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ohio. This is where the agency
does most of
its research on fires in the
weightless environment

40:03.234 --> 40:05.303 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of space called microgravity.

40:05.336 --> 40:11.576 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GARY RUFF: They used water foam
fire extinguishers
that they had, but that probably
at most just

40:11.609 --> 40:14.746 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
kind of cooled everything else
around it and
kept it from spreading.

40:14.779 --> 40:21.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Ruff leads a team
that is trying
to learn more about big fires in
space. So,

40:21.452 --> 40:25.256 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the plan is to deliberately set
one and watch
what happens, really.

40:25.290 --> 40:27.358 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
All right, so what are we
looking at here,
David?

40:27.392 --> 40:29.427 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID URBAN, NASA: This is the
Saffire-III
module.

40:29.460 --> 40:34.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: David Urban is
the principal
investigator for the Spacecraft
Fire Experiment,

40:34.932 --> 40:36.868 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
or Saffire.

40:36.901 --> 40:43.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We spoke beside Saffire-III,
slated for launch
at the end of 2016. The one
currently in space,

40:43.574 --> 40:50.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Saffire-I, is an identical box
strapped inside
a cargo ship. Once the craft
makes its delivery,

40:50.381 --> 40:55.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
departs and is a safe distance
from the International
Space Station, it will be time
to light the

40:55.553 --> 40:58.222 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
fire inside Saffire.

40:58.256 --> 41:00.124 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Fire on a spacecraft is a pretty
scary thing,
isn't it?

41:00.158 --> 41:03.594 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID URBAN: It's a very small
space. What
you would normally tolerate in
your house

41:03.628 --> 41:05.496 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are completely non-tolerable in
a spacecraft.

41:05.530 --> 41:11.903 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: NASA's most
painful fire lesson
came in 1967, when three
astronauts were killed

41:11.936 --> 41:19.243 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
during a countdown test on the
launchpad in
Florida. It prompted a lot of
changes in spacecraft

41:19.277 --> 41:25.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
designs. The agency took great
pains to eliminate
flammable materials wherever
possible.

41:25.450 --> 41:28.453 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But fires in microgravity are
harder to predict.

41:28.486 --> 41:32.190 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A lot of unanswered questions
about fires
in microgravity, right?

41:32.223 --> 41:35.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID URBAN: A huge number.
Basically, we
don't really know how fast they
will grow

41:35.960 --> 41:41.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or how large they will get, nor
do we really
understand, given the way the
spacecraft are

41:41.132 --> 41:45.336 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
built, how quickly that
temperature and pressure
rise will be a problem for the
crew.

41:45.370 --> 41:50.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: On the ground,
when you light
a candle, the heat of the flame
melts the

41:50.908 --> 41:56.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
wax. It pulls up into the wick.
It vaporizes,
and that is what fuels the
flame.

41:56.681 --> 42:02.253 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So if gravity is pushing
everything downward,
what is it that makes a flame go
upwards?

42:02.286 --> 42:08.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, as it turns out, the flame
is surrounded
by higher-pressure air. And
gravity is pulling

42:08.259 --> 42:13.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
down colder, denser air, meaning
there is
more pressure at the base of the
flame. That's

42:13.631 --> 42:20.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what causes the flame to go up.
It's buoyancy.
